ST <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=jenterra>jenterra</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 27<br> <font color=#3333ff>(1/20/03 4:38 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=82.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_cry.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: The War On Drugs</span><hr size=1> Where to begin. . .<br>
<br>
My father spent over twenty years of his life as a special agent for the DEA.  His life was routinely in danger as he worked the drug-related homicide task force in Miami, as he followed heroin traffickers from Thailand through Europe to the US, and as judges and agents in high profile cases received death threats from Colombian drug lords.  He and I have discussed the war on drugs - which accounted for a huge part of his life - at great length, and he agrees completely with what I have to say on the matter.<br>
<br>
The war on drugs, as it is currently being waged, cannot be won by the US.  Period.  The only effective way to wipe out this criminal empire is by eliminating the &quot;criminal&quot; aspect, since it is clear that we will never, ever eliminate the &quot;empire&quot; itself.  By decriminalizing the drug industry, we gain the upper hand.   Why?  Basic laws of supply and demand come into play -- legalization would bring drugs out of the back allies and result in legally regulated suppliers, which in turn brings prices down and eventually brings about the end of the &quot;drug lords.&quot; (This is an over-simplification, but it is the general idea).  It would also de-stygmatize drugs and make treatment programs more readily available and effective.<br>
<br>
Americans will spend over $100 BILLION this year alone in arresting, prosecuting, incarcerating, and parolling drug users.  $100 Billion to deal with &quot;victimless&quot; crimes.  <br>
<br>
Repeated studies have shown that people on drugs do not commit crimes -- it's people looking to get money for their next drug purchase who perpetrate crimes.  Eliminate the criminal aspect, lower prices, and allow treatment facilities to supply drugs to junkies in a regulated, gradual reduction program, and you eliminate the crimes these people might have committed to try and get their drugs under our current system.  <br>
<br>
I spent many years in Switzerland, where the government considers drugs a medical issue, not a legal one.  Free needle programs, free treatment facilities. . .yet they maintain one of the highest standards of living, longest life expectancies, and lowest infant mortality rates in the world.  They have a literacy rate of 100% and offer free university-level education to all citizens.  Technically, drugs are not &quot;legal&quot;, and Swiss officials cooperate with American law enforcement in stopping large shipment of drugs from the Far East that are bound for the US.  But NO ONE is jailed for possession, and drug addicts are offered help, not harassment.  Stronger, healthier society?  Without a doubt.<br>
<br>
Jen<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#9fb7df><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dbc67@religiousdebate60574>DBC67</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Convicted Skeptic</span><br>  Posts: 153<br> <font color=#3333ff>(1/20/03 4:41 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=82.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_exclamation_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: re: War on Drugs</span><hr size=1> Okay, to contrast any two positions you need to examine both sides.  What has the war on drugs earned us that it would be preferable to no waging said war?  Well, as cited already, we have over crowded prisons.  What else do we have?  Lost revenues.  Violence. Deaths.  <br>
<br>
Lost revenues is probably the weakest argument and the most obvious.  No one really does check that box on their income taxes for ‘undeclared income’ and reports their drug sales.  Anyone can see how taxing a recreational drug industry would realize profit.  Just how much you may not know though.  The US Gov’t purchases pharmaceutical grade cocaine (100% pure) at a cost of $35 per vial retail.  The vials are 5 gram vials so it is $7 per gram for use in the medical industry (yes, it has a medicinal purpose and cocanimides are the root drug of many anesthetics and analgesics.)  Contrast this 100% pure vial against the $50 1/8 gram of 40-70% pure product.  <br>
<br>
50% pure 1/8 gram at $50 = $4,000 for that same $35 vial which was ALREADY profitable at $35.<br>
<br>
Furthermore, it isn’t just revenues that are lost.  Our prisons are full of ZERO TOLERANCE drug offenders.  Yet when you look at the record, it is never the Drug Lords in prison, it is the petty dealer or possessor.  They were arrested for having it in their possession.  They were arrested for trafficking in it.  Yet 90% of those traffickers are small time and only sold enough to others to support their own habits.  They didn’t go out and threaten anyone to get them to try it, they are sought out or seduced into selling it by friends who are mistrustful and want their friends to sell to them so they feel safe.  Hardly worth my money each year.  I’d prefer paying someone to keep Jeffrey Dahlmer out of my neighborhood.<br>
<br>
Why do we have deaths?  Well for one, because it isn’t regulated, drug quantities are subject to the tolerances of their market.  The coke you buy in Seattle is of a different grade from that in LA.  Harder to get means more tolerant of a lesser grade product. Let’s say you are a young musician who grew up snorting in Seattle then got a big record deal in LA.  You are used to snorting 3 inches of coke to get high.  You go to LA and buy some that is supposed to be ‘the best’ and it is far more pure than what you are used to in Seattle. For the sake of debate let’s call it 50% pure (WA) vs 70% pure (CA), after all 100% pure is a liquid at room temperature and would kill anyone.  Now then, our intrepid musician snorts his 3 inch line, gets far more than he has ever had in his life, goes into cardiac arrest and dies to the loss of fans every where.  How many times have we seen this same story?  So regulation to standardize naming, labeling, purity, etc is to societies benefit.  Can’t do that if it is illegal.  Perhaps if you equated it to drinking a 16 ounce beer in your home, then going to a bar the next night and ordering the same drink but getting a 16 oz glass of grain alcohol or vodka and pounding it down.  You wouldn't expect it, nor could you control for it.<br>
<br>
Now the least obvious aspect, violence.  Why do we have so much violence around drugs?  People do them to feel good, right?  So why shoot anyone for it?  Well, the first thing you lose when drugs become illegal is access to the law enforcement and court systems in transactions involving drugs.  If you are cutting into my sales territory, I can’t call the cops.  If you sell me a junk product, I can’t sue you.  If you take all my money or product, I have NO recourse.  The only way I can respond is with violence and taking retributive action myself.  With this basic template, the groups that survive and remain profitable in the drug industry are those who are good at violence.  Success in violence is rewarded failure is eliminated.  Furthermore, the crime wrapped around the industry is present in any industry, but it is without recourse.  If a kid wants a Nintendo game and can’t afford it, he might shoplift, or mug an old woman in the park, or steal from mom and dad.  The same thing will happen in any area, but with drugs, the cost is so high and the recourse so impossible that the crimes are reflective of it.  You can’t mug an old lady for a kilo of coke, you need to hit a liquor store, and a pretty successful one at that.  You don’t want a coke-head driving around?  Well we don’t want drunk driving either, so why should it be any different?  We also don’t want anyone driving during the rapture or sex or an epileptic seizure.  So criminalize THAT, not the unnecessary part.  If you want to lay on your floor at home stoned out of your mind, or drunk, or playing Nintendo, or watching porn, or reading bible verses, or other mindless wastes of time, go ahead.  It is not for me to criticize.  Freedom dictates that those are your choices and should have the right to make them.<br>
<br>
Gov’t should act in the best interests of protecting society, not in deciding for itself what people should act like and forcing them to conform (beyond basic safety, obviously.)  Coca growers in South America and abroad grow coca because it is hugely profitable for them as a commodity.  Not because they are evil and want to undermine US culture.  They have families and no car and want to feed their kids just like you and me.  They can grow an acre of coca and carry bushels to a refining plant (a tent with water and a brick to mash the plant) for 1,000 times the money the same acre of corn would yield.  Legalize it and the profit disappears and they go into a different marketable commodity that is more profitable.  <br>
<br>
Yes, I think we would be better off if it were legal.<br>
<br>
One last thing to consider.  Large-scale synthetic plants like DuPont and Dow Chemical would hate to see hemp (the stalk of cannabis AKA marijuana) legalized.  It is an incredibly cheap alternative to their synthetic solutions developed once hemp became illegal.  They will always fund the counter-choice programs for gov’t interdiction and restrictions on our freedom.  It is profitable for them.  Hemp ropes from colonial times are still on display at many historic seaports and museums.  How pleasing would the same display of yellow nylon rope look? <p>DBC67<br>
<br>
