 <p><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Hands above your head, and you won't even feel me...</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> </p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#9fb7df><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dynamohumm6>dynamohumm6</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.pro-rock.com/ikonboard/avatars/clutch-elephant1.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Rocket Queen</span><br>  Posts: 47<br> <font color=#3333ff>(1/21/03 3:21 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=82.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.clipartconnection.com/img/6/WB/zed_non_com/clipconxn/animations/science/0563.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_exclamation_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: heres more..</span><hr size=1> I want to add a little bit more specifically dealing with decriminalization of specific drugs. <br>
<br>
More than ten million americans smoke marijuana regularly. Seventy-seven million americans have tried marijuana at least once in their life. <br>
<br>
In countries where marijuana has been decriminalized, there has a been a significant decrease in the sales and consumption of tobacco and alcohol. <br>
<br>
Alcohol is of course legal, but drinking by minors has declined dramatically over the last twenty years. (Daily use by minors declined from 6.9% to 2.5% between 1979 and 1993.) Experience in Europe suggests that decriminalization does not seem to have an independent influence. There are also risks inflicted on minors by forcing pot underground, including insuring that consumption will never take place under adult supervision, contact with shady characters, and subjecting young people to the tender mercies of the drug war, including arrests and the possible loss of grants, student loans, and jobs. <br>
Marijuana prohibition needlessly destroys the lives and careers of literally hundreds of thousands of good people each year in this country. More than 700,000 Americans were arrested on marijuana charges last year, and more than 5 million Americans have been arrested for marijuana offenses in the past decade. Almost 90 percent of these arrests are for simple possession, not trafficking or sale. This is a misapplication of the criminal sanction that invites government into areas of our private lives that are inappropriate and wastes valuable law enforcement resources that should be focused on serious and violent crime. <br>
<br>
<br>
There is no conclusive evidence that the effects of marijuana are causally linked to the subsequent use of other illicit drugs. Preliminary animal studies alleging that marijuana &quot;primed&quot; the brain for other drug-taking behavior have not been replicated, nor are they supported by epidemiological human data. Statistically, for every 104 Americans who have tried marijuana, there is only one regular user of cocaine, and less than one user of heroin. Marijuana is clearly a &quot;terminus&quot; rather than a gateway for the overwhelming majority of marijuana smokers. <br>
<br>
In Holland, where politicians decided over 25 years ago to separate marijuana from the illicit drug market by permitting coffee shops all over the country to sell small amounts of marijuana to adults, individuals use marijuana and other drugs at rates less than half of their American counterparts. <br>
<br>
According to the U.S. Institute of Medicine (IOM), fewer than one in 10 marijuana smokers become regular users of the drug, and most voluntary cease their use after 34 years of age. By comparison, 15 percent of alcohol consumers and 32 percent of tobacco smokers exhibit symptoms of drug dependence. <br>
<br>
And don't even get me STARTED on medical marijuana. <br>
<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
So, like most members of NORML, I am looking for the removal of all criminal penalties for for the private possession and responsible use of marijuana by adults, including the cultivation for personal use, and the casual nonprofit transfers of small amounts. <br>
NORML additionally supports the development of a legally controlled market for marijuana, where consumers could purchase it from a safe, legal and regulated source. <br>
<br>
As for heroin/cocaine/etc....I think it's less cut &amp; dry. I do not think possession of an amount suitable for personal use should be illegal. Sending smack addicts to prison does nothing except allow them to continue their addiction inside prison walls. <br>
A former friend of mine got arrested for robbery recently (to support his heroin addiction) and chose prison over rehab, because you can still get smack in prison. 'Nuff said.<br>
<br>
I'm not saying heroin et al is good stuff. I've lost several good friends to heroin, and I'm watching one of my best friends slip away because of the shit. He's been in and out of rehab 5 times this past year. Accessibility has never been an issue for him, and he lives in the middle of nowhere in rural Pennsylvania.He's $15,000 in debt because of cash advances on his credit cards to buy heroin.<br>
Now, I can't help but think that if there were some kind of program--a &quot;we'll sell you this much heroin a week, at this price, on the condition that you attend rehab&quot; and wean people off of the shit...something similar to methadone.<br>
The way it is now, the programs they do don't help at all. <br>
My friend with the problem went to a methadone clinic to try and get clean. They drug tested him, said he didn't have enough heroin in his system to qualify for the program. So, he went home and almost overdosed on h <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>so he could get help</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
How fucked is that? I don't have a well mapped system for what should be done with the hard drugs, but what we're doing now is NOT WORKING. The system has GOT to be changed.<br>
More later...<br>
Emmy<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
